  <!-- S7 WHY TRUST US -->
  <section id="trust">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Why Trust This African Grey vs Macaw Comparison?</h2>
    <p>A Grey breeder ranking Greys against macaws owes you the bias disclosure up front — so here it is, along with the experience that still makes the comparison worth reading.</p>
    <div class="author-card">
      <img class="ac-banner" src="/african-grey-parrot-breeder-midland-tx-hero.webp" width="800" height="600" alt="Two of the C.A.Gs African Greys beside a hand-written Rony and Rose, Midland, Texas sign" loading="lazy">
      <div class="ac-row">
        <img class="ac-avatar" src="/birds/bery/bery-grey-african-parrot-for-sale.webp" width="128" height="96" alt="Bery, a hand-raised Congo African Grey at the C.A.Gs aviary in Midland, TX" loading="lazy">
        <div><h3 class="ac-name">Mark &amp; Teri Benjamin</h3><p class="ac-sub">Midland, TX · hand-raising Greys since 2014</p>
          <p class="ac-badges"><span>USDA-licensed</span><span>CITES papers</span><span>DNA-sexed</span><span>PCR-screened</span></p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>A lot of Grey-versus-macaw content online comes from sites that sell neither bird, or from macaw breeders with an obvious thumb on the scale. Mark and Teri Benjamin have hand-raised African Greys at C.A.Gs since 2014, and fielded "why not a macaw instead?" from prospective buyers for nearly that long. Every Grey claim below traces to our own aviary; every macaw claim traces to a cited study, an avian veterinary source, or conversations with macaw breeders and rescues we've built relationships with over a decade — not a guess dressed up as expertise.</p>
    <p>Fair warning cuts both ways here. We'll say outright that a macaw beats any Grey on visual drama, and that a Blue-and-Gold can bond to its person just as fiercely. What we refuse to do is borrow another site's uncited bite-force figure or unverified macaw claim because it sounds confident — every specific number on this page has a source we can point to.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">How We Think About Health-Documentation ROI</h3>
    <p>Sticker price is a rounding error next to the decades that follow — so we spend the effort upfront, on the paperwork that actually protects a bird for that long: viral PCR screening, a sexing certificate, a vet exam, a hatch record with a permanent leg band, and the captive-bred CITES filing that keeps everything above-board. Full terms sit on our <a href="/african-grey-parrot-health-guarantee/">health guarantee page</a>, regardless of which bird this page ultimately points you toward.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S8 DEEP DIVE: AFRICAN GREY (kept lean — full depth lives on the CvT/cockatoo pages; this page's word count belongs to the macaw side) -->
  <section id="grey">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Makes the African Grey the Talking Champion?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/timneh-vs-congo-african-grey-real-photo-box.webp" srcset="/timneh-vs-congo-african-grey-real-photo-box-760.webp 760w, /timneh-vs-congo-african-grey-real-photo-box.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" alt="A Congo and a Timneh African Grey side by side on a perch, showing the Congo's bright red tail against the Timneh's darker maroon tail and horn-colored beak" loading="lazy">
    <p>Plain silver-grey plumage hides the trait that actually decides this comparison: a working vocabulary and contextual reasoning that no macaw species has matched in any published study. We go deep on Grey biology on our <a href="/congo-vs-timneh-african-grey/">Congo vs Timneh comparison</a>, so this section stays brief on purpose — the word count on this page belongs to the macaw half of the equation. Current Congo and Timneh chicks are posted on their own <a href="/congo-african-grey-for-sale/">Congo</a> and <a href="/timneh-african-grey-for-sale/">Timneh</a> availability pages.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Does a Grey's Size Stack Up Against a Macaw's?</h3>
    <p>A Congo weighs 400–600 grams at 12–14 inches; a Timneh runs smaller, 275–375 grams. Both live 40–60 years with proper care — squarely inside macaw territory, so neither bird wins on "shorter commitment."</p>
    <a class="inf" href="/congo-african-grey-for-sale/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-size-in-macaw-context.webp" srcset="/african-grey-size-in-macaw-context-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-size-in-macaw-context.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="An African Grey drawn to scale between the smallest Hahn's Macaw and the largest Hyacinth Macaw, showing where the Grey sits on the size range" loading="lazy"></a>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">What Is an African Grey's Temperament Like?</h3>
    <p>Reserved rather than performative. A Grey reads a room before it joins in, and it shows attachment through proximity and conversation instead of constant physical contact — nearly the opposite instinct from most macaws, covered later on this page.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Is an African Grey Right for an Apartment?</h4>
    <p>Generally, yes. A Grey's vocal habits — talking, whistling, appliance mimicry — stay in a range thin walls survive, which is the single biggest reason we steer apartment shoppers toward a Grey over nearly any macaw. The decibel gap gets its own section further down this page.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">How Does an African Grey Bond?</h4>
    <p>Slowly, then completely, usually landing on one household member who earns it. It reads as a quieter devotion than a macaw's full-body physicality — a Grey wants to share the room with you, not climb you.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">What Grey Owners Notice in Week One</h5>
    <p>A subdued opening week is normal, not a warning sign — a new Grey is auditing its household before it relaxes into one. Families expecting an instant performer sometimes worry for nothing; the character arrives on the bird's own schedule.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: the day Maxy started talking</h6>
    <p>Maxy, our homepage video's talking Grey, chose "Teri" as his first functional word, then added "bye bye" once he'd clocked that it worked — vocabulary picked for outcome, not just repeated for its own sake. It's the single anecdote we point to when someone doubts a Grey actually reasons about language.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Which Health Risks Do We Screen African Greys For?</h3>
    <p>Two conditions matter most: hypocalcemia, a documented grey-specific risk tied to calcium handling and managed with diet plus real UV-B light, and feather-destructive plucking, which tracks boredom far more reliably than genetics. Our full symptom-by-symptom breakdown — including the exact lighting protocol every buyer takes home — lives on the <a href="/african-grey-vs-cockatoo/#grey">African Grey vs Cockatoo health section</a>, since it's identical screening regardless of which comparison page brought you here.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Hypocalcemia Explained: the Grey's Calcium Weak Spot</h4>
    <p>Untreated low calcium shows up as weakness or, in severe cases, seizures. Plucking is nearly always an enrichment gap dressed as a medical problem. Every buyer leaves with our written diet and lighting plan, not a generic pellet suggestion.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">What Our PBFD and Polyomavirus Screen Catches</h5>
    <p>A lab-verified PCR result on the individual bird for both viral diseases — not a sentence on a listing promising the seller "screens for everything."</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: World Parrot Trust profiles for both species</h6>
    <p>Species facts above track the <a href="https://www.parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">World Parrot Trust's <em>Psittacus erithacus</em> profile ↗</a>.</p>
  </section>

