  <!-- S9 DEEP DIVE: MACAW FAMILY -->
  <section id="macaw">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Are Macaws Really Like to Live With?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-macaw-family-side-by-side-box.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-macaw-family-side-by-side-box-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-macaw-family-side-by-side-box.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" alt="An African Grey photographed beside macaws, showing the size, color and body-mass gap between the two genera" loading="lazy">
    <p>"Macaw" isn't a species — it's a whole genus spread across a 130-gram Hahn's on one end and a 1,700-gram Hyacinth on the other, and daily life with one bears little resemblance to daily life with a Grey. A Grey's currency is intellect; a macaw's is spectacle — saturated color, outsized personality, and a volume most houses simply weren't designed to absorb. All 11 species get their own spotlight further down; first, what unites them.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Big Do Macaws Get — From Mini to Hyacinth?</h3>
    <p>The range is the whole story. A Hahn's Macaw at 130–170 grams is lighter than a Timneh Grey. A Blue-and-Gold runs 900–1,300 grams. A Hyacinth tops the entire parrot world at up to 1,700 grams and 40 inches nose to tail. Anyone who says "macaws are big birds" without naming a species is skipping the size chart's most useful line — the species section below exists precisely to fill that gap.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why Do Owners Call Macaws "Velcro Birds" With an Attitude?</h3>
    <p>Because a well-bonded macaw wants physical contact and involvement — on your shoulder, chewing your buttons, narrating its opinions at volume — in a way a reserved Grey never asks for. For the right owner, that constant, boisterous engagement is the entire appeal. The catch is the flip side of that same energy: a macaw denied stimulation doesn't quiet down, it escalates into screaming or feather destruction.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">How Loud and Demanding Is a Macaw, Really?</h4>
    <p>Loud enough to reset the whole comparison. A macaw's contact call is instinctive, built in the wild to carry over a mile of rainforest canopy, and large species produce some of the loudest sounds in aviculture. Through shared apartment walls, that isn't a nuance — it's a lease violation waiting to happen. This is the single biggest reason we point apartment buyers toward a Grey.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">Why Macaws Fill So Many Rescues</h5>
    <p>The volume and the space demands together. A macaw kept in a too-small cage with too little flight time doesn't adapt quietly — it screams, chews destructively, or plucks. Rescues report large macaws among their most common intake, usually from owners who underestimated the sustained commitment. Greys get surrendered too, typically from boredom-driven plucking, but macaw rehoming runs on a different scale entirely.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: species-appropriate housing standards</h6>
    <p>Minimum cage and flight-time guidance here reflects standard avicultural practice published by avian veterinary and rescue organizations; we've kept the figures conservative rather than aspirational.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Are Macaws as Smart as African Greys?</h3>
    <p>Genuinely intelligent, just aimed differently. Dr. Irene Pepperberg's decades of work with Alex the Grey established language and contextual reasoning as the species' signature; macaw intelligence shows up more in problem-solving, foraging persistence and social learning than in vocabulary. Neither bird is the "dumb" one — they're solving different problems.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Enrichment Prevents Plucking — in Both Genera</h4>
    <p>The behavioral principle holds for macaws exactly as it does for Greys: a parrot with real foraging work to do rarely turns on its own feathers, and a bored one often does. A macaw's bigger beak just means bigger, tougher enrichment — a reason the toy budget for large species runs $200–$300 a month.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">Citation: contrafreeloading research context</h5>
    <p>The contrafreeloading principle — that parrots choose to work for food even when it's freely available — comes from studies on Greys and cockatoos summarized by <a href="https://lafeber.com/pet-birds/inside-dr-pepperbergs-lab-greys-vs-umbrella-cockatoos-who-likes-to-work-for-their-food/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lafeber ↗</a>; we apply the same enrichment logic to macaws as sound general parrot-care practice, not as a claim that macaws were part of that specific study.</p>
  </section>

