  <!-- S14 NOISE / APARTMENT -->
  <section id="noise">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Which Is Louder — and Can a Macaw Live in an Apartment?</h2>
    <p>More placements fail over noise than over price. <strong>Short version: the Grey is dramatically quieter, and close to the only one of the two that genuinely works in shared housing.</strong></p>
    <p>Picture a volume dial: a Grey sits in the middle, cycling through whistles, talking and mimicked appliance beeps at fairly predictable times of day. Large macaws max the dial out — a Blue-and-Gold alone can clear 100 decibels, chainsaw territory, a call shaped by evolution to travel a mile through dense canopy. Your neighbors will notice which bird you chose.</p>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-care-guide/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-macaw-noise-meter.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-macaw-noise-meter-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-macaw-noise-meter.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Noise meter placing an African Grey&#39;s moderate chatter well below a large macaw&#39;s contact scream of over 100 decibels" loading="lazy"></a>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Which Macaw Species Is Quietest?</h3>
    <p>If your heart is set on a macaw but you have neighbors, the mini species — Hahn's, Severe — are the least loud of the group, simply by having smaller lungs and a smaller resonating chamber. They're still a macaw's scream, not a Grey's chatter. There's no silent macaw; there's only "less catastrophic," and the mini species are where that road ends.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S15 DANDER -->
  <section id="dander">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Powder Down, Dander &amp; Allergies — the Honest Version</h2>
    <p>Here's a genuine point in the macaw's favor that few Grey-focused pages admit: <strong>macaws are not powder-down birds, and typically produce less feather dust than a Grey.</strong></p>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-care-guide/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-macaw-dander-allergy.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-macaw-dander-allergy-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-macaw-dander-allergy.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Dander comparison showing the African Grey as a high powder-down bird and the macaw as a low-dust bird, the one metric where the macaw wins" loading="lazy"></a>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Is One Bird Safer for Allergy Sufferers?</h3>
    <p>African Greys rank among the dustiest parrots kept as pets; a case report indexed by the <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9381342/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">U.S. National Library of Medicine ↗</a> traced one owner's hypersensitivity pneumonitis directly to their Grey's feather dust. Macaws skip true powder down entirely and generally throw off less airborne particulate — real, but not the same claim as "safe for allergy sufferers," since droppings and dried food dust can still trigger sensitivity regardless of species.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">What This Means in Practice</h4>
    <p>If dander is your deciding factor and you're set on a bird with real talking ability, that combination doesn't exist cleanly in either direction — a macaw's lower dust comes bundled with the noise and space tradeoffs covered above. Anyone with asthma or bird allergies should spend real time around adult birds of either kind before committing, and budget for an air purifier regardless.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Bottom Line for Allergy-Prone Homes</h5>
    <p>Regular bathing or misting reduces a Grey's feather dust; a HEPA purifier near the cage clears what goes airborne. Neither measure is optional if allergies run in your household — for either species.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S16 NUTRITION (macaw-unique section) -->
  <section id="nutrition">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Should a Grey Eat vs What Should a Macaw Eat?</h2>
    <p>This is the section almost no comparison page runs, and it matters: <strong>Greys and macaws have genuinely different nutritional pressure points.</strong></p>
    <a class="inf" href="#nutrition"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-macaw-nutrition-comparison.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-macaw-nutrition-comparison-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-macaw-nutrition-comparison.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Diet comparison contrasting the African Grey&#39;s calcium and UV-B needs against the macaw&#39;s higher-fat Brazil nut and macadamia requirement" loading="lazy"></a>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why African Greys Need Calcium and UV-B Light</h3>
    <p>Greys regulate calcium differently than most parrots, and a diet or lighting shortfall shows up as a medical emergency, not a slow decline. A pellet-forward diet, calcium-bearing fresh vegetables, and genuine UV-B exposure — full-spectrum lighting or safe supervised sun — are non-negotiable parts of a Grey's care plan from day one.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">What Happens Without Enough Vitamin D</h4>
    <p>Without adequate UV-B, a Grey can't properly synthesize the vitamin D it needs to absorb dietary calcium, regardless of how much calcium is on the plate. The chain breaks at the light, not the food bowl — a detail plenty of care sheets skip.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">Hypocalcemia Warning Signs</h5>
    <p>Weakness, tremors, and in severe cases seizures — hypocalcemia is preventable but not automatically prevented, which is why we send every buyer home with our exact lighting and diet plan rather than a generic pellet recommendation.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why Macaws Need More Fat — Brazil Nuts and Macadamias</h3>
    <p>Macaws evolved cracking oil-rich palm nuts, and their digestive systems expect a higher fat intake than a Grey's — Brazil nuts and macadamias in moderation are a standard part of a healthy macaw diet, not a treat-only indulgence. Get this wrong in either direction — too little fat, or too much as the whole diet — and macaw-specific health problems follow.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/mix-nuts-for-african-greys-box.webp" srcset="/mix-nuts-for-african-greys-box-760.webp 760w, /mix-nuts-for-african-greys-box.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" alt="A bowl of mixed nuts and seeds of the kind fed in moderation at the C.A.Gs aviary, the fat-rich foods a macaw needs far more of than a Grey" loading="lazy">
    <h4 class="cag-h4">How Beak Size Drives Your Toy Budget</h4>
    <p>The same beak strength that lets a macaw crack a Brazil nut also demolishes wooden toys and perches on a schedule — realistically $200–$300 a month for the larger species, since an under-enriched macaw redirects that same cracking instinct toward cage bars, furniture, or its own feathers.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The $200–$300 Monthly Reality for Large Macaws</h5>
    <p>Budget for destruction, not just nutrition, when a large macaw is the plan — it's a recurring cost most first-time macaw shoppers underestimate, and one a Grey's smaller beak simply doesn't generate at the same scale.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: avian nutrition sources</h6>
    <p>Species-specific dietary needs above reflect established avian veterinary nutrition guidance, including the resources at <a href="https://www.aav.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the Association of Avian Veterinarians ↗</a>.</p>
  </section>

