  <!-- S18 WHICH FITS + QUIZ -->
  <section id="household">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Which Parrot Fits Your Household?</h2>
    <p>Scores are useful; households are specific. Find your situation below, then try the quiz for a direct read on your particular case — it's the same rundown we give over email.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Find Your Household Match</h3>
    <p>Answer honestly about your space, noise ceiling and experience, and the flow below lands you on the bird your household can actually sustain.</p>
    <div class="match-grid">
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Brand-New Bird Owners</h4><p>Start with a Grey. A macaw's noise and space demands blindside most newcomers within the first year, and neither bird forgives casual research — but the Grey's learning curve is survivable for a first-timer in a way a Blue-and-Gold's usually isn't. Set on a macaw regardless? A mini species and months of reading first.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Households With Children</h4><p>The bite-force math alone points to the Grey. A large macaw's beak strength is a real supervision burden around small children, on top of the volume. Neither bird belongs unsupervised near toddlers — this is a decades-long relationship, not a trial pet.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Condo and Apartment Realities</h4><p>Grey, without much debate — it's nearly the only one of the two that shared walls tolerate. A mini macaw species is the sole exception worth researching, and even then, your neighbors are part of the decision.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">You Want Bold Color &amp; Presence</h4><p>That's a macaw's household to win. No Grey will visually dominate a room the way a Scarlet or Hyacinth does — choose honestly by that want, then plan around the volume and square footage it demands.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Long-Hours Professionals</h4><p>Pause before either. A parrot left alone most of the day is how plucking starts in a Grey and screaming escalates in a macaw — the macaw usually unravels faster. If your schedule is genuinely tight, waiting a year may beat buying now.</p></div>
    </div>

    <a class="inf" href="#household"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-macaw-lifestyle-flowchart.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-macaw-lifestyle-flowchart-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-macaw-lifestyle-flowchart.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Lifestyle flowchart routing apartment dwellers and first-time owners toward the African Grey and experienced keepers with space toward a macaw" loading="lazy"></a>
