  <!-- S19 COST -->
  <section id="cost">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Does an African Grey Cost vs a Macaw?</h2>
    <p>Our Greys run $1,700–$3,500 for a Congo and $1,500–$1,600 for a Timneh, deposit $200. Macaw prices swing wildly by species — a few hundred for a mini species, five figures for a rare Hyacinth — numbers we're citing from the wider breeder and marketplace world, not selling ourselves, since C.A.Gs raises African Greys exclusively. <a href="/african-grey-parrot-price/">Our price guide</a> carries the current per-bird Grey pricing.</p>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-price/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-macaw-cost-breakdown.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-macaw-cost-breakdown-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-macaw-cost-breakdown.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Cost breakdown comparing an African Grey&#39;s purchase price and first-year budget against a macaw&#39;s larger cage, food and toy-replacement costs" loading="lazy"></a>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why the Sticker Price Is the Cheap Part</h3>
    <p>Whichever bird you pick, the purchase is a rounding error next to what feeds, vets, toys and cages cost over 40-plus years — and a macaw's bigger footprint plus faster beak-driven destruction stack its ongoing bill well above a Grey's. Watch the cheap end of either market especially closely: a listing with no CITES paperwork or sexing certificate is where fraud complaints concentrate.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">What's Included in Our Grey's Price</h4>
    <p>Nothing gets itemized separately: CITES papers, DNA sexing certificate, avian-vet health certificate, hatch record with the closed band number, and clean PBFD/Polyomavirus PCR results all ride inside the sticker price. Shipping is the only add-on — $185 airport, $350 door.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">Budgeting Year One After the Purchase</h5>
    <p>Plan on roughly $825–$2,000 beyond the purchase price in year one for a Grey: cage, starter perches and toys, an initial wellness exam, a year of pellets, and enrichment rotation. A comparable macaw budget runs noticeably higher across nearly every one of those same categories.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: our no-unweaned-chicks policy</h6>
    <p>Discount unweaned chicks show up constantly online, Grey and macaw both. We won't touch that market: hand-feeding mistakes kill babies, and every bird leaving C.A.Gs is already fully weaned before a buyer ever meets it.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Try It: First-Year Budget Estimator</h3>
