    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Do the First 30 Days With a Grey Look Like?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/bonding-african-grey-parrot-first-30-days-box.webp" srcset="/bonding-african-grey-parrot-first-30-days-box-760.webp 760w, /bonding-african-grey-parrot-first-30-days-box.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" alt="A hand-raised African Grey bonding with its keeper at C.A.Gs during the first weeks before going home" loading="lazy">
    <p>What follows describes a Grey specifically, since that's the bird we place — the general shape holds for any large parrot brought home for the first time. Teri walks every buyer through this timeline before pickup, precisely so week two doesn't feel like a step backward.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Settling-In Timeline, Phase by Phase</h3>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">1</span><b>Days 1–3 · Landing</b><p>A quiet, low-perched bird that eats only once the room clears isn't stressed — it's a Grey doing exactly what a Grey does when it lands somewhere new.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">2</span><b>Week 1 · Reading the Room</b><p>Your Grey is cataloging the household — voices, footsteps, meal timing. Give it a routine boring enough to memorize; predictability is the whole point right now.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">3</span><b>Week 2 · Building Trust</b><p>Step-ups stop being a negotiation, fingers get trusted with treats, and you'll likely hear the first attempted echo of something specific to your house.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">4</span><b>Weeks 3–4 · The Real Bird Shows Up</b><p>Personality arrives in earnest around the time we call to check in — every buyer keeps our direct line through this whole first month.</p></div>
