  <!-- S21 MYTHS -->
  <section id="myths">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">African Grey vs Macaw Myths We Bust Weekly</h2>
    <p>Parrot forums recycle the same handful of confident claims, and new buyers show up repeating them as settled fact. A few deserve a closer look.</p>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-guide/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-macaw-myths-reality.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-macaw-myths-reality-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-macaw-myths-reality.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Myths versus reality cards correcting the claims that all macaws are equally loud and that a cuddly macaw is a low-maintenance macaw" loading="lazy"></a>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Myths We Hear Most</h3>
    <div class="myth-grid">
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"Macaws are all roughly the same volume."</strong> Not remotely — a Hahn's scream and a Blue-and-Gold's scream aren't in the same league, even though both outpace a Grey. The species name inside "macaw" carries more weight than the umbrella term.</p></div>
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"A cuddly macaw is a low-maintenance macaw."</strong> The physical affection is genuine, but it comes bundled with screaming, chewed-through furniture, and distress the moment contact stops. There's no version of macaw temperament without the demands attached.</p></div>
    </div>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">The Big One: "Macaws Are Friendlier, Greys Are Cold"</h4>
    <p>The most repeated claim in this whole match-up deserves its own verdict, because it steers buyers wrong in both directions at once.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Reality: Two Kinds of Love</h5>
    <p>Grey attachment runs just as deep — it simply reads differently, expressed through watching, talking and staying close rather than through touch. Call a Grey "cold" and you're usually describing a bird that's newly arrived or under-socialized, not describing the species. Macaw affection, meanwhile, always ships with its demands attached. Warmth isn't the variable; the delivery method is.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: owner reports across both groups</h6>
    <p>This tracks what large-parrot communities report consistently: Greys engaged but self-contained, macaws affectionate but exacting — a real trend, never a guarantee for any individual bird.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S22 SUCCESSION -->
  <section id="succession">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">They Can Outlive You: Lifespan &amp; Succession Planning</h2>
    <p>Most comparison pages skip this entirely, and it matters more than the talking gap or the noise gap: <strong>you may not outlive either bird.</strong> A Grey runs 40–60 years; a large macaw can push toward 80. Buy at 40 and you could still be arranging care at 100 — and a parrot without a plan often passes through a dozen or more homes before it dies.</p>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-lifespan/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-macaw-lifespan-succession.webp" srcset="/african-grey-macaw-lifespan-succession-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-macaw-lifespan-succession.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Lifespan timeline showing an African Grey at 40 to 60 years and a large macaw at 50 to 80 years against a human owner&#39;s planning horizon" loading="lazy"></a>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">What a Parrot Succession Plan Includes</h3>
    <p>Nothing complicated, just documented: someone who's agreed to take the bird and actually spent time with it, one folder holding the CITES paperwork, health records and band number, and a small set-aside fund or clear instructions for the handoff itself.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Why Some Parrots See 20 Homes in a Lifetime</h4>
    <p>A 40-to-80-year lifespan will outlast marriages, careers, health, and eventually the owner — that's just the math, not a pessimistic take. Skip the successor plan and someone else inherits a crisis instead of a companion.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">Starting Your Own Plan Today</h5>
    <p>One conversation is the entire cost of entry: pick the person, let them get to know the bird, file the paperwork somewhere they'll actually find it. Grey or macaw, this step belongs in every decades-long parrot purchase, not an afterthought for later.</p>
    <aside class="cta-strip">
      <div class="cs-copy"><span class="cs-kick">Planning for the long haul?</span><p>We keep our direct line open for the life of every bird we place, successor conversations included.</p></div>
      <a class="btn-strip" href="#reserve">Talk to Mark & Teri</a>
    </aside>
  </section>

