  <!-- S23 CITES -->
  <section id="cites">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">CITES Status &amp; Documentation — What Paperwork Comes With Every Bird?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/timneh-african-grey-cites-documented-box.webp" srcset="/timneh-african-grey-cites-documented-box-760.webp 760w, /timneh-african-grey-cites-documented-box.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" alt="Evie, a CITES-documented Timneh African Grey at C.A.Gs, photographed with the paperwork folder that travels with every bird" loading="lazy">
    <p>Every African Grey, Congo or Timneh, sits at CITES Appendix I — the treaty's tightest category, applied in 2017 after wild trapping had thinned native populations severely. Macaws split: most commonly kept species land at Appendix II, while the Hyacinth carries Appendix I status alongside the Grey. Ownership stays legal either way — what changes is how hard you have to work to prove the bird was captive-bred.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Appendix I Paperwork, Explained Without the Legalese</h3>
    <p>Per the <a href="https://www.fws.gov/law/wild-bird-conservation-act" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Wild Bird Conservation Act, as enforced by the U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service ↗</a>, wild-trapped Appendix-I birds cannot legally enter the country as pets. A documented, home-bred bird moves between owners without issue, and the closed band on a Grey's leg — sealed on in the nest, physically impossible to add later to a wild adult — is the proof that outlasts any sales receipt.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">What IUCN Status Means for Greys and Macaws</h4>
    <p>Wild population status runs separately from legal trade status: the Congo Grey is IUCN-rated Endangered, the Timneh Vulnerable, and among macaws the Hyacinth is Vulnerable with several smaller species facing their own habitat pressure. None of it affects your captive-bred bird's legality — it's simply why we frame documentation as a conservation stance, not a sales feature.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">Why Captive-Bred Documentation Matters More Than Ever</h5>
    <p>Every documented, home-bred sale removes one financial incentive to pull a bird from a wild population — a Grey or any macaw, whichever paper trail you're checking before you buy.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: CITES appendix listings + IUCN assessments</h6>
    <p>Source data: the <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES appendices database ↗</a> and <a href="https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22724813/154068024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IUCN Red List ↗</a> listings for <em>Psittacus erithacus</em>, <em>Psittacus timneh</em>, and the macaw species named on this page.</p>
  </section>

